<subSubSection id="C30FB2903529FFE4FF47F87AFDBDFF4D" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="367" pageId="10" pageNumber="366" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3529FFE4FF47F87AFDBDFF4D" blockId="10.[151,1437,1783,2026]" lastBlockId="11.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="367" pageId="10" pageNumber="366">
<emphasis id="B9613D093529FFE5FF47F87AFEE1F85E" bold="true" box="[199,334,1928,1954]" pageId="10" pageNumber="366">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet comes from the Spanish (“ 
<collectingCountry id="F302A18B3529FFE5FC84F87AFCD8F85E" box="[772,887,1928,1954]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="366">Colombia</collectingCountry>
en paz” = “ 
<collectingCountry id="F302A18B3529FFE5FC7CF87AFBC2F85E" box="[1020,1133,1928,1954]" name="Colombia" pageId="10" pageNumber="366">Colombia</collectingCountry>
in peace”), in honor to the recent peace process in the country of the authors, the country that almost all Colombians dream of, and which we hope to construct in the near future. To be treated as an arbitrary combination of letters, and hence without the need to agree in gender with the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903528FFE4FF47FF48FAC9FEBD" pageId="11" pageNumber="367" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3528FFE4FF47FF48FAC9FEBD" blockId="11.[151,1436,151,321]" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">
<emphasis id="B9613D093528FFE4FF47FF48FEEDFF28" bold="true" box="[199,322,186,212]" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C159A983528FFE4FE36FF49FDD2FF29" authority="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez, 2022" authorityName="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez" authorityYear="2022" box="[438,637,187,213]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Thrandina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="367" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="colombiaenpaz" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9613D093528FFE4FE36FF49FDD2FF29" box="[438,637,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">T. colombiaenpaz</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9613D093528FFE4FD05FF49FD70FF29" bold="true" box="[645,735,187,213]" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25280723528FFE4FD05FF49FD70FF29" box="[645,735,187,213]" pageId="11" pageNumber="367" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be recognized from those of the remaining species in the genus by their larger proventral apophysis of the tibia (PvTa), curved embolus (e), and their smaller median apophysis (ma) (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3528FFE4FF5BFEF1FEF1FEE1" box="[219,350,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURES 44–50" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1549,1573]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,466,1522]" captionTargetId="figure-181@12.[151,1435,453,1526]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 44–50. T. colombiaenpaz sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8263), 44 male palp, prolateral view; 45–46 same, ventral view; 47–48 same, retrolateral view; female paratype (ICN-Ar 8264), 49 epigynum, ventral view; 50 same, cleared, dorsal view. Abbreviations: cd=copulatory duct, co=copulatory opening, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, PvTa=proventral tibial apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, RvTa=retroventral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct, sp=spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.20 mm (44–48), 0.10 mm (49–50)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">Figs 44–48</figureCitation>
). Females can be diagnosed by their bigger anterior copulatory opening of the epigynum, and the ventral and posterior insertion of the copulatory ducts in their bigger and rounded spermathecae (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3528FFE4FB56FED5FAF5FEBD" box="[1238,1370,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 44–50" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1549,1573]" captionTargetBox="[159,1423,466,1522]" captionTargetId="figure-181@12.[151,1435,453,1526]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 44–50. T. colombiaenpaz sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 8263), 44 male palp, prolateral view; 45–46 same, ventral view; 47–48 same, retrolateral view; female paratype (ICN-Ar 8264), 49 epigynum, ventral view; 50 same, cleared, dorsal view. Abbreviations: cd=copulatory duct, co=copulatory opening, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, PvTa=proventral tibial apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, RvTa=retroventral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct, sp=spermatheca. Scale bars = 0.20 mm (44–48), 0.10 mm (49–50)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501148" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501148/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="367">Figs 49–50</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
